



# 1️⃣ Call by Value vs Call by Reference

This is one of the MOST IMPORTANT concepts in C++.

---

# First Understand the Big Idea

When you pass a variable to a function:

👉 Does the function get:

* a **copy** of data?
  OR
* the **original variable itself**?

That creates:

* Call by Value
* Call by Reference

---

# Part A — Call by Value

---

## Simple Idea

👉 Function receives a **copy** of the variable.

Original remains unchanged.

---

## Real-World Example

Think of this:

```text id="bxqklr"
Original document → photocopy
```

If you write on photocopy:
👉 Original does NOT change.

---

## Example

```cpp id="26wzpr"
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

void change(int x)
{
    x = 100;
}

int main()
{
    int a = 10;

    change(a);

    cout << a;
}
```

---

## Output

```text id="f65xw2"
10
```

---

## Why?

Because:

```text id="p6qj2u"
change(a)
```

creates COPY:

```text id="n1qjlwm"
x = 10
```

Only copy changes.

Original `a` stays same.

---

## Memory Visualization

```text id="0ocgmf"
a → 10

Function call:
x → 10   (separate copy)
```

Different memory locations.

---

## Mental Model

```text id="4s0f8m"
Call by Value = duplicate data
```

---

# Part B — Call by Reference

---

## Simple Idea

👉 Function gets DIRECT access to original variable.

Changes affect original.

---

## Real-World Example

Instead of photocopy:

```text id="5ofn1t"
You give original document itself
```

Now changes are permanent.

---

## Example

```cpp id="0udom0"
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

void change(int &x)
{
    x = 100;
}

int main()
{
    int a = 10;

    change(a);

    cout << a;
}
```

---

## Output

```text id="ws4s9y"
100
```

---

## Why?

`&x` means:

```text id="6rtn98"
x is another name for a
```

No copy created.

---

## Memory Visualization

```text id="a9i58q"
a → 10

x → same memory location
```

---

## Mental Model (VERY IMPORTANT)

```text id="y7fj9z"
Reference = nickname for original variable
```

---

# Key Difference

| Call by Value                 | Call by Reference       |
| ----------------------------- | ----------------------- |
| copy sent                     | original sent           |
| changes don’t affect original | changes affect original |
| safer                         | faster                  |
| more memory                   | less memory             |

---

# Why Reference is Useful

Imagine huge data:

```text id="r5avxf"
100000 elements
```

Copying is expensive.

Reference avoids copying.

👉 Faster programs.

---

# Connection to Pointers

Reference internally behaves similar to pointer.

Both work with:

* original memory
* addresses

---

# How to Remember Forever

```text id="nyj1h9"
Value → copy
Reference → real object
```

OR

```text id="rfr5q4"
Value = photocopy
Reference = original paper
```

---

# 2️⃣ Dynamic Memory Allocation (`new` and `delete`)

This is where C++ becomes powerful 🔥

---

# First Understand the Problem

Normal variables:

```cpp id="z78d6x"
int x;
```

are stored in:

```text id="0tvv5g"
STACK memory
```

Created automatically.
Destroyed automatically.

---

## Problem

What if size is decided at runtime?

Example:

```text id="x9uqkh"
User enters number of students
```

We don’t know size beforehand.

---

# Solution → Dynamic Memory

Memory created while program runs.

---

# Using `new`

## Example

```cpp id="7vjlwm"
int* p = new int;
```

---

## What Happens?

1. Memory created in:

```text id="j9r20v"
HEAP memory
```

2. Address returned

3. Pointer stores address

---

## Assign Value

```cpp id="86mdv8"
*p = 50;
```

---

## Access Value

```cpp id="1xbx84"
cout << *p;
```

Output:

```text id="uxmbtw"
50
```

---

# Memory Visualization

```text id="h6w7ri"
Heap:
Address 200 → 50

Pointer p → 200
```

---

# Why Heap Memory Exists

Stack memory is:

* limited
* automatic

Heap memory gives:

* flexibility
* dynamic size

---

# VERY IMPORTANT — `delete`

Memory in heap is NOT removed automatically.

So:

```cpp id="cz5f7h"
delete p;
```

---

# Why Delete Matters

Without delete:

```text id="z6jsao"
Unused memory keeps occupying RAM
```

This is called:

# 🔥 Memory Leak

Very important interview topic.

---

# Mental Model

```text id="1pyqqh"
new → rent memory
delete → return memory
```

---

# Dynamic Array Example

```cpp id="g34x9g"
int n;
cin >> n;

int* arr = new int[n];
```

Now array size depends on user input.

---

# Connection to What You Already Know

Static array:

```cpp id="0u58rv"
int arr[5];
```

Fixed size ❌

Dynamic array:

```cpp id="g7dy9s"
new int[n];
```

Flexible ✅

---

# Common Mistake 🔥

```cpp id="0x7j3g"
delete p;
cout << *p;   // ❌ dangerous
```

Why?

Memory already deleted.

Pointer now points to invalid memory.

Called:

# Dangling Pointer

---

# How to Remember Forever

```text id="bhnjlwm"
new → create memory
delete → destroy memory
```

